default&#xa0;
defaultWe understand the Government’s desire to enhance consumer protection but we do not believe that a one size fits 
defaultall approach necessarily works. Certain protections, which may operate without any great difficulty in one scenario, may cause difficulties for both providers and consumers in another. In those areas which we have highlighted above, we believe that the spe
defaultcific measures proposed will cause difficulty in relation to services which involve the immediate delivery of digital content. It is easy to envisage them requiring changes to the delivery systems which will degrade rather than enhance the consumer’s use o
defaultf the services. 
default&#xa0;
defaultUKCTA believes that the Government ought to look very carefully at the issues we have highlighted and to consider whether in these limited areas, the electronic communications sector ought to be exempt from these particular regulations.  
defaultT
defaulthere is 
defaultalready established 
defaultprecedent for this course of action within BIS’s attempts to implement the Regulations.  
defaultRegulation 6 provides that the Regulations do
default 
defaultn
defaulto
defaultt apply to contracts for services of a banking, insurance or
default&#xa0;
defaultinvestment nature.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultUKCTA und
defaulterstands this approach was adopted because Government felt that 
defaultregulation of the financial sector was better addressed through sector specific legislation. 
defaultUKCTA believes that the practical difficulties which we have described suggest that the same approa
defaultch ought to be followed in relation to the Electronic Communications sector. 
